import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;

public class VulnerableCode {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Vulnerable code: using a relative path to load a file
        File file = new File("C:\\Users\\username\\Desktop\\secret.txt");
        try {
            String contents = new String(file.listFiles()[0].getAbsolutePath());
            System.out.println(contents);
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error reading file");
        }
    }
}
```
This code is vulnerable because it uses a relative path to load a file, which can lead to a path traversal attack. An attacker could manipulate the file path to access sensitive files on the system.

***

[code snippet 2]
```java
import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;

public class SecureCode {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Secure code: using a absolute path to load a file
        File file = new File("C:\\path\\to\\secure.txt");
        try {
            String contents = new String(file.toURI().toURL().openStream().readAllBytes());
            System.out.println(contents);
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error reading file");
        }
    }
}
```
This code is secure because it uses an absolute path to load a file, which makes it more difficult for an attacker to manipulate the file path. Additionally, the code uses the `toURI()` and `toURL()` methods to ensure that the file path is properly encoded and validated.

Note that in a real-world scenario, you would want to handle errors and exceptions more robustly, and also consider using a more secure way to load files, such as using a library like Apache Commons IO.

